<div class="page-wrap">

  <!-- INTRODUCTION -->
  <section id="introduction">
    <div class="section-label">Introduction</div>
    <h2>Why Shoulder Pain Is So Common — And What You Can Do About It</h2>
    <p>Shoulder pain is one of the most common complaints among busy adults — especially those spending hours at a desk, behind a wheel, or carrying heavy loads through the day. It rarely arrives dramatically. It creeps in as tightness when reaching overhead, a pinching feeling when lifting bags, or stiffness that's worst in the morning.</p>
    <p>The good news: many cases of shoulder pain in otherwise healthy adults are influenced by movement habits, strength deficits, and muscle imbalances rather than serious structural injury. The front of the body is overused. The back is underused. The muscles that control the shoulder blade have lost their coordination. No amount of rest alone fixes that.</p>
    <p>The research is clear about what does work:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Scapular (shoulder blade) stability training</li>
      <li>Balanced pushing and pulling movements</li>
      <li>Progressive loading at pain-free ranges</li>
      <li>Consistency — not intensity</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>The Bottom Line</strong>
      <p>You don't need a complicated program. You need the right four movements, done consistently, at the right dose. This guide gives you exactly that — no gym required, no prior fitness experience needed.</p>
    </div>
    <h3>Equipment Needed</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Wall</li>
      <li>Pair of dumbbells (2–15 lbs)</li>
      <li>Optional: incline bench</li>
      <li>Optional: resistance band</li>
    </ul>

