  <!-- EXERCISES -->
  <section id="exercises">
    <div class="section-label">Section 2</div>
    <h2>The 4-Movement Shoulder System</h2>

    <!-- Exercise 01 -->
    <div class="exercise-card">
      <div class="exercise-card-header">
        <div class="ex-number">01</div>
        <div class="ex-title-block">
          <div class="ex-number-label">Exercise One</div>
          <div class="ex-name">Facing Wall Slide + Lift-Off</div>
          <div class="ex-subtitle">Scapular Control &amp; Shoulder Mobility</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="exercise-card-body">
        <div class="ex-section-title">What It Is</div>
        <p>A bodyweight drill performed facing a wall. Forearms rest on the wall at shoulder width. You slide your arms upward while reaching slightly forward into the wall, then briefly lift your forearms 1–2 inches off the surface at the top.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">Why It Matters</div>
        <p>Facing the wall removes the temptation to compensate with lumbar extension and directly trains serratus anterior and upward rotation mechanics — the movement pattern most impaired in adults with shoulder pain and impingement.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">How It Improves Daily Life</div>
        <p>Reaching overhead, placing items on shelves, lifting luggage, and drying your hair all require the shoulder blade to rotate and tilt correctly. This exercise restores that pattern safely.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">3 Coaching Cues</div>
        <ul class="cue-list">
          <li>Gently press forearms into the wall throughout — don't let contact drift.</li>
          <li>Slide up slowly, reaching long through the wall as you rise.</li>
          <li>At the top: lift without shrugging — reach forward, not upward.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="rx-grid">
          <div class="rx-cell starter">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Starter Prescription</div>
            <p>2–3 sets × 8–12 reps<br>3 sec up / 3 sec down<br>2–3x per week</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell progression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Progression</div>
            <p>Add a light dumbbell (2–5 lbs) once wall contact is consistent throughout.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell regression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Regression</div>
            <p>Reduce range of motion. Only slide as high as you can without losing forearm contact.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="key-cue"><strong>Key Cue:</strong> "Reach long through the wall, then lift without shrugging."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Exercise 02 -->
    <div class="exercise-card">
      <div class="exercise-card-header">
        <div class="ex-number">02</div>
        <div class="ex-title-block">
          <div class="ex-number-label">Exercise Two</div>
          <div class="ex-name">Neutral-Grip Overhead Press</div>
          <div class="ex-subtitle">Safe Overhead Strength</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="exercise-card-body">
        <div class="ex-section-title">What It Is</div>
        <p>A dumbbell pressing movement with palms facing each other (neutral grip) throughout. Performed seated or standing with ribs down and glutes lightly engaged for spinal control.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">Why It Matters</div>
        <p>A neutral grip reduces internal rotation stress at the shoulder joint compared to a traditional pronated grip — making it significantly safer for adults with shoulder sensitivity while still building real overhead strength.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">How It Improves Daily Life</div>
        <p>Placing items on high shelves, lifting carry-on luggage overhead, and any reaching task above shoulder height.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">3 Coaching Cues</div>
        <ul class="cue-list">
          <li>Ribs down, glutes lightly engaged — don't let your lower back arch as you press.</li>
          <li>Press the dumbbells slightly forward on the way up, not straight back overhead.</li>
          <li>Stop two reps before failure — this is a strength-building movement, not a burnout set.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="rx-grid">
          <div class="rx-cell starter">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Starter Prescription</div>
            <p>2–3 sets × 6–10 reps<br>Stop 2 reps before failure<br>2–3x per week</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell progression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Progression</div>
            <p>Add 2–5 lbs once all reps are completed with clean form. Slow the lowering phase to 3 seconds.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell regression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Regression</div>
            <p>Reduce to 5 lbs or less. Limit range of motion if overhead feels uncomfortable. Seated only.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="key-cue"><strong>Key Cue:</strong> "Ribs down, press slightly forward — not straight back."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Exercise 03 -->
    <div class="exercise-card">
      <div class="exercise-card-header">
        <div class="ex-number">03</div>
        <div class="ex-title-block">
          <div class="ex-number-label">Exercise Three</div>
          <div class="ex-name">Lateral Raise (Controlled)</div>
          <div class="ex-subtitle">Shoulder Endurance &amp; Joint Balance</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="exercise-card-body">
        <div class="ex-section-title">What It Is</div>
        <p>A dumbbell raise performed to shoulder height with a slow, controlled lowering phase. Elbows are slightly bent throughout and momentum is eliminated entirely.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">Why It Matters</div>
        <p>Weakness in the lateral deltoid and rotator cuff contributes to the "pinchy" impingement feeling when raising your arm. The controlled tempo forces the muscles to work through their full range rather than relying on momentum.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">How It Improves Daily Life</div>
        <p>Reaching to the side, carrying bags, and any activity requiring your arm to work away from your body all depend on this pattern.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">3 Coaching Cues</div>
        <ul class="cue-list">
          <li>Lead with your elbows and keep your thumbs slightly higher than your pinkies.</li>
          <li>Raise only to shoulder height — going higher increases impingement risk.</li>
          <li>Lower in 2–3 seconds every rep. The slow descent is where the work happens.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="rx-grid">
          <div class="rx-cell starter">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Starter Prescription</div>
            <p>2–3 sets × 12–15 reps<br>2–3 sec lowering phase<br>2–3x per week</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell progression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Progression</div>
            <p>Add 2 lbs once all reps are completed with a full 3-second lower. Then slow to 4 seconds.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell regression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Regression</div>
            <p>Use 2–3 lb dumbbells or perform without weight. Focus entirely on the controlled lowering phase.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="key-cue"><strong>Key Cue:</strong> "Lead with elbows, thumbs slightly higher than pinkies. Shoulder height only."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Exercise 04 -->
    <div class="exercise-card">
      <div class="exercise-card-header">
        <div class="ex-number">04</div>
        <div class="ex-title-block">
          <div class="ex-number-label">Exercise Four</div>
          <div class="ex-name">Chest-Supported Upper Back Row</div>
          <div class="ex-subtitle">Upper Back Strength &amp; Posture Correction</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="exercise-card-body">
        <div class="ex-section-title">What It Is</div>
        <p>A dumbbell row performed with your chest resting on an incline bench or leaning forward against a supported surface. Elbows pull out slightly wide, targeting the rear deltoid, mid-trapezius, rhomboids, and rotator cuff together.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">Why It Matters</div>
        <p>Many adults are significantly undertrained in the posterior shoulder and upper back. This creates the rounded-forward posture that puts constant strain on the neck, shoulder, and mid-back. The chest-supported position eliminates lower back involvement and isolates exactly the muscles that need the most work.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">How It Improves Daily Life</div>
        <p>Standing taller throughout the day, reducing neck tension from desk work, pulling open heavy doors, and restoring the postural baseline that protects your shoulders during all other activities.</p>
        <div class="ex-section-title">3 Coaching Cues</div>
        <ul class="cue-list">
          <li>Pull with your elbows, not your hands — lead elbows out and back.</li>
          <li>Squeeze your shoulder blades together at the top. Hold for one second.</li>
          <li>Keep your core braced — don't let your lower back sag.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="rx-grid">
          <div class="rx-cell starter">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Starter Prescription</div>
            <p>2–3 sets × 10–15 reps<br>Controlled pace throughout<br>2–3x per week</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell progression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Progression</div>
            <p>Slow the lowering phase to 3 seconds. Increase weight by 2–5 lbs when all reps are fully controlled.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rx-cell regression">
            <div class="rx-cell-label">Regression</div>
            <p>Use a light resistance band anchored at chest height if a bench isn't available. Focus on form first.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="key-cue"><strong>Key Cue:</strong> "Pull elbows wide, squeeze shoulder blades, hold for one second."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

